The '''jinnalaluo''' (also called '''kimnaras''', '''feiren''', and '''yeishen''') were divine creatures with human bodies and animal's heads that were featured in [[Buddhism|Buddhist mythology]].<ref name="Chinese mythology">{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=Jeremy|title=Chinese mythology, A to Z|year=2010|publisher=Chelsea House|location=New York|isbn=9781604134360|edition=2nd}}</ref>

== Description ==
These beings resemble human bodies and have the heads of animals, most notably horses or birds.<ref name="Chinese mythology" />

== Role in Chinese mythology ==
They are celestial musicians, whose music is said to fill Heaven. They play a variety of instruments and are linked to a very ancient Indian art form, where they are portrayed as [[bird-of-paradise|birds-of-paradise]].

